ollaborator?\n    52→\n    53→Welcome everyone. I'm Jane Developer, and today we're going to explore how AI is fundamentally changing the way we build software.\n    54→\n    55→[PAUSE:500]\n    56→\n    57→This isn't about AI replacing developers. It's about AI amplifying what developers can do.\n    58→<!-- /AUDIO -->\n    59→\n    60→**Speaker Notes:**\n    61→- Make eye contact with the audience\n    62→- Gauge the room's technical level\n    63→- Pause for effect after the hook\n    64→\n    65→---\n    66→\n    67→## [hook-problem] The Current State\n    68→\n    69→![The Problem](images/slide-02-hook.png)\n    70→\n    71→<!-- AUDIO -->\n    72→[TRANSITION] But first, let's talk about where we are today.\n    73→\n    74→The software development landscape is facing unprecedented challenges.\n    75→\n    76→[KEY_POINT] Development cycles are getting shorter while complexity is increasing exponentially.\n    77→\n    78→Teams are expected to deliver more features, faster, with fewer bugs. And the tools we've been using for decades are struggling to keep up.\n    79→\n    80→[PAUSE:300]\n    81→\n    82→Sound familiar?\n    83→<!-- /AUDIO -->\n    84→\n    85→**Speaker Notes:**\n    86→- Rhetorical question to engage audience\n    87→- Let the statistics on the next slide speak for themselves\n    88→\n    89→---\n    90→\n    91→## [evidence-stats] By the Numbers\n    92→\n    93→![Statistics](images/slide-03-stats.png)\n    94→\n    95→<!-- AUDIO -->\n    96→[EVIDENCE] Let me share some data that might surprise you.\n    97→\n    98→According to recent studies, developers spend only 30% of their time actually writing new code. The rest goes to debugging, reading documentation, and context switching.\n    99→\n   100→[KEY_POINT] That's 70% of our working hours on tasks that don't directly add value.\n   101→\n   102→[PAUSE:400]\n   103→\n   104→Imagine if we could reclaim even half of that time.\n   105→<!-- /AUDIO -->\n   106→\n   107→**Speaker Notes:**\n   1